    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-21T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-21T16:00:00-05:00" n="670"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d670">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">600.119/1794: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-21T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 21, 1918—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3595. For Sheldon [from War Trade Board]: No. 1902. Embassy’s 4480 December 10, 4
                    p.m., transmitting Weddell’s December 8, 7 p.m.<note n="39" xml:id="d670fn39"
                        >Not printed. Alexander W. Weddell was War Trade Board representative at
                        Athens.</note> Repeat following reply to Weddell:</p>
                <pb facs="0857" n="769" xml:id="pg_769"/>
                <p rend="flushleft">7 p.m.<note n="39" xml:id="d670fn40">Not printed. Alexander W.
                        Weddell was War Trade Board representative at Athens.</note> Repeat
                    following reply to Weddell: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“We believe that under present conditions there should be no unnecessary
                            restrictions left upon commerce and cannot see that at the present time
                            we are in any way interested as to the possibility of Greece obtaining
                            more than her actual needs of any one commodity. It would be impossible
                            to comply with your suggestion that ration details as fixed by the
                            Commercial Bureau be maintained unless licenses are referred to Athens
                            before granting. We therefore propose to make public announcement on
                            December 26 that beginning January 1, 1919 licenses will be issued
                            freely for shipments to Greece without prior reference to Athens. These
                            licenses will be valid regardless of the flag of the steamer, will be
                            unlimited as to time, and will be valid for shipment either direct or
                            via any other country. We can see no object in cabling particulars of
                            these licenses after granting.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
